				\begin{document}$$k$$\end{document}k. This assumption is in line with findings on wisdom of crowds showing that individuals produce unbiased judgments on average (Larrick & Soll, 2006; Steyvers et al., 2009). Whereas there is ample evidence for the validity of wisdom of crowds in general (Davis-Stober et al., 2014; Larrick & Soll, 2006; Surowiecki, 2004), this assumption may be inadequate under certain conditions. For instance, judgment processes can lead to non-normal distributions (Hueffer et al., 2013; Lorenz et al., 2011; Lorenz, 2021) or extreme judgments (Thomas et al., 2021) in which the mean of the judgments does not longer reflect the correct answer. However, for the present purpose of comparing the accuracy of independent and dependent judgments, this is not a critical assumption given that it is made both for wisdom of crowds and for sequential collaboration (skewed distributions are considered in the empirical study below).

