An alternative approach is to assume a bias directly for the mean of the internal distribution of plausible judgments. Similar to the bias introduced via skewness of the distribution, biases affecting the mean of the distribution can be expected to be reduced by expertise since experts overall provide highly accurate judgments (Budescu & Chen, 2014; Davis-Stober et al., 2014). We extended the computational model described above with an expertise-dependent bias \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$B_k$$\end{document}Bk of the mean of the internal distribution of plausible judgments. The assumed amount of bias is larger for individuals with lower expertise and smaller for individuals with higher expertise:13\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} Y_{ik} \sim \text {Normal}(\mu = T_k + B_k E_i, \sigma = D_k E_i). \end{aligned}$$\end{document}Yik∼Normal(μ=Tk+BkEi,σ=DkEi).The evaluation of the plausibility of the presented judgment in sequential collaboration as well as the updated distribution of plausible values were extended accordingly.

Figure 7 displays sequential collaboration and unweighted averaging of independent judgments for A) an unbiased normal distribution, B) a biased normal distribution, and C) a skew normal distribution of plausible values. The bias was set to \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$B_k = 0.6$$\end{document}Bk=0.6 and the skewness was set to \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$S_k = 0.25$$\end{document}Sk=0.25 which result in the same mean \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$M = 0.6$$\end{document}M=0.6 for the internal distribution of plausible values with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_i = 1$$\end{document}Ei=1. This reflects a bias of 20% in terms of the standard deviation. A bias induced by a skewed normal distribution results in more accurate judgments in sequential collaboration compared to unweighted averaged independent judgments over a sequential chain. In contrast, a bias of the mean of the normal distribution of plausible judgments results in less accurate judgments in sequential collaboration compared to unweighted averaged independent judgments. According to the model, the gap in performance between sequential collaboration and unweighted averaging increases as the amount of bias of the mean of the internal distribution of judgments increases. Due to the anchoring bias implemented in the model and the assumed reduction in standard deviation, large biases to the mean of the internal distribution of plausible values result in collaborative estimates that move away from the correct answer. Even though the extended computational model makes such a prediction, we do not expect this to occur in experimental settings. Instead, we assume that larger biases occur due to a combination of a bias to the mean of the underlying distribution and skewness of this distribution. Some evidence that a bias is at least partially induced by skewness has been demonstrated in our empirical study showing that a skew normal distribution best captures the response patterns of our participants.

